<DOCNO> AP890428-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a new experiment confirms observations from the 
controversial cold fusion research announced last month giving 
very encouraging evidence for fusion a scientist says 
the new experiment generated more power than it consumed and 
showed two other signs of possible fusion said researcher uziel 
landau 
but results so far are only preliminary and we stop short of 
saying that we see fusion said landau a professor of chemical 
engineering at case western reserve university in cleveland 
fusion is the nuclear reaction that powers the sun and some 
scientists hope to harness it as an environmentally benign power 
source it occurs when the cores of two hydrogen atoms fuse 
last month researchers announced at the university of utah that 
they had produced fusion at room temperature with a simple 
apparatus conventional fusion research uses extremely high 
temperatures and complex machinery 
since the announcement some scientists have reported similar 
results while others said their attempts to confirm the work failed 
landau worked with two large test tubes each containing a small 
palladium rod to act as one electrode and a titaniumcoated 
platinum mesh to serve as the other 
the electrodes were placed in a bath of socalled heavy water 
in which hydrogen is replaced by a chemical cousin called 
deuterium the liquid also contained lithium landau said thursday 
in an interview 
according to proponents of cold fusion the reaction occurs in 
one of the electrodes when current is applied 
landau said his apparatus produced three possible signs of 
fusion 
one was that the apparatus gave off 8 percent to 30 percent more 
power than it consumed with the output given off as heat he said 
the apparatus also produced bursts of extremely tiny particles 
called neutrons 
and the heavy water solution showed about a doubling of its 
initial concentration of tritium which is a form of hydrogen 
landau said 
landau said he did not test for production of helium a product 
of fusion 
future experiments will use ordinary water rather than heavy 
water landau said scientists say that can help rule out the 
possibility that a chemical reaction rather than a nuclear 
reaction produced the experimental results 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
