<DOCNO> AP890428-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here is an outline of the structure of the soviet 
communist party and government 
party structure 
the communist party holds political power in the soviet union 
but president mikhail s gorbachev has proposed changes that allow 
some contested elections to form a legislature that may exercise 
significant political power 
the communist partys power is centered in the politburo and the 
secretariat of the partys central committee 
the communist party congress which has 5000 elected members 
is supposed to be the partys supreme organ and ordinarily meets 
every five years the congress elects the central committee made 
up of 250 to 300 of the countrys top leaders it now has 251 
members 
the central committee normally meets about twice a year to 
approve policies and formally elects the members of the politburo 
and the secretariat the two highest party bodies 
since march 11 1985 gorbachev been general secretary of the 
communist party head of the secretariat and leading member of the 
politburo since oct 1 1988 gorbachev also has been the nations 
president holding top party and government jobs 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the secretariat 
this communist party body is responsible for running social and 
economic spheres as well as party personnel and ideology and 
wields tremendous power over implementation of policy politburo 
membership and a seat on the secretariat traditionally have been 
considered necessary to gain the top party job there are now 10 
secretaries including gorbachev 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the politburo 
gorbachev runs meetings of the politburo the partys most 
powerful body it now has 12 full members and eight candidate or 
nonvoting members the politburo normally meets every week 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
government structure 
the supreme soviet 
the 1500 members are elected from a single slate of approved 
candidates and theoretically make up the top government body in the 
soviet union but it has traditionally met only twice a year to 
ratify policy set by the communist party 
under a reform pushed through by gorbachev the supreme soviet 
will become a smaller body with about 500 members that meets 
several months a year gorbachev says he wants it to be more 
active handling operational questions the party apparatus has 
assumed over the years and leaving the party to decide policy 
questions but the supreme soviet has not met under the new format 
and the extent of its powers is uncertain 
the presidium of the supreme soviet 
the presidium which has 37 members is the collective 
presidency that gorbachev leads as chairman presidents of each of 
the 15 soviet republics are members the presidium has the power to 
issue government decrees when the supreme soviet or parliament is 
not in session but the presence of politburo and regional party 
leaders in its membership ensures its actions have prior toplevel 
approval 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
council of ministers 
the council the soviet unions cabinet is responsible for 
daytoday operation of government ministries such as agriculture 
or transportation it is headed by premier nikolai i ryzhkov a 
full member of the politburo 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
congress of peoples deputies 
the congress of peoples deputies is a new 2250member body 
consisting of 1500 deputies elected from geographical 
organizations and 750 elected from the party and its affiliates 
social professional and trade union organizations 
the congress which was elected in the first multicandidate 
balloting is empowered to choose the president and the supreme 
soviet from among its members amend the constitution and review 
the presidents choice for premier 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
ostracized by the state department confined 
to the city limits afghanistans top diplomat in washington leads 
a frustrating existence 
miagol the first last and only name of afghanistans charge 
daffaires is hoping the recent pullout of 115000 soviet troops 
from his country will ease some of the isolation imposed on him by 
the united states but he is also realistic 
the sovieteducated economist invited secretary of state james 
a baker iii to his embassys reception thursday evening marking 
the 11th anniversary of the revolution that brought to power a 
marxistoriented government and resulted in the 1979 soviet 
invasion 
they said he couldnt come unfortunately miagol said with 
a skeptical laugh 
very few americans attended the reception which drew mostly 
diplomats from soviet bloc and other communist and socialist 
countries 
for a man who has to ask permission every time he wants to leave 
the city and is usually turned down miagol was remarkably 
cheerful at an interview in the resplendent redbrick mansion which 
doubles as residence and embassy 
physically our life is good he said but morale is 
difficult 
miagol one of 15 children does not know how old he is but 
estimates his age at about 40 my mother said there was snow on 
the ground but she didnt know in what year he said 
miagol arrived here 10 months ago with his russian wife and two 
children when he asked to travel to new york by car to attend the 
general assembly meetings of the un last fall he was told to go 
by plane 
when he asked permission to drive to the soviet embassys 
recreation compound outside washington he was denied they said 
it was too far but people from other socialist embassies also have 
25mile limit and they are allowed to go miagol said 
the united states and other countries impose 25mile travel 
limits on diplomats from countries deemed unfriendly 
this makes me nervous miagol said he spends his days 
reading messages received by telex from kabul dealing with 
administrative matters relating to his threeman embassy and 
keeping in touch with the extensive community of afghan exiles in 
washington 
his only contact with the state department is through richard 
gookin head of the protocol department whom he sees about twice a 
month i give him my opinions miagol said 
gookin listens politely hes a very nice man and conveys 
miagols views to state department experts but gookin refused to 
accept a written message from afghanistans leader najibullah 
congratulating george bush on his inauguration as president and 
expressing his hopes for improved relations miagol said 
they told me to put the envelope in a window for letters at 
the state department he said miagol said he used the same window 
to deliver a second message several weeks ago asking the united 
states to stop arming the mujahedeen rebels 
the rebels backed by the united states and pakistan fought the 
soviet occupation for nine years and are now locked in a civil war 
with najibullahs sovietbacked government 
the united states continues to view najibullah as a hardline 
marxist and fails to see that he is gaining acceptance by afghans 
as the only viable choice for leading the warwracked country 
miagol said 
they must learn from the mistakes of the soviets who didnt 
understand the afghan people miagol said 
neither the soviets nor the americans understand that afghans 
cannot embrace marxism he said it is not right with our 
culture with our religion said the sovieteducated moslem 
the united states withheld recognition from afghanistans 
government after the soviets invaded contending it was not elected 
democratically and does not represent the afghan people however 
the us embassy continued to function in kabul serving as a 
listening post in the sovietrun country 
the united states recognizes many governments that are not 
democratic that are fascist dictatorships miagol said at least 
