<TEXT>
nasa designing systems in which 
three or four seconds is forever has developed a 
graphicsoriented computer program to help flight controllers react 
to launch emergencies 
atlantis with five astronauts aboard was scheduled to launch 
at midafternoon today 
in the seconds and minutes after liftoff nasa is to make its 
most extensive use of a flight control system which highlights 
potential hazards with colorful displays 
past mission managers had to sort through mindnumbing columns 
of data on blackandwhite monitors that date back to the gemini 
era of the 1960s 
the new system inaugurated at mission control after the 1986 
challenger disaster gives nasa controllers three or four more 
seconds to order a shuttle into an emergency landing in case of a 
sudden failure after liftoff 
three to four seconds in a lot of different failure modes is 
forever says senior nasa controller john f muratore 
from typewriterstyle keyboards controllers can now punch up 
graphics that trace the shuttle trajectory duplicate cockpit 
instrument displays and even mimic the horizon as the astronauts 
see it from inside their rising space ship 
the national aeronautics and space administration is designing 
artificial intelligence programs to help plug its brain drain 
as thousands of experienced apollo era employees retire the 
generic name for such programs is expert systems 
nasa has begun implementing its expert system at the mission 
control center in houston as part of a multimilliondollar 
improvement program scheduled for completion in 1991 muratore is 
in charge of developing the system 
nasa hopes expert systems can capture the knowledge of veteran 
employees to help younger workers do various jobs muratore 
predicted his system will cut months off the minimum time of two 
years that controllers must spend in training before being assigned 
to a flight 
they have to make a mental picture of whats going on with the 
shuttle muratore explained we took some senior controllers 
and learned how they built their mental models then programmed the 
computer to do that for them 
when shuttles returned to flight in september nasa installed 
the expert system to help engineers pinpoint trouble in the 
orbiters three main engines it ran in tandem with the traditional 
system 
we were prepared to take actions based on the new program 
muratore said i dont know of any other case where somebody has 
built an expert system and then put life and property on the line 
that way 
since then muratore said the system has become a primary 
tool for four controllers who monitor communications engines 
mechanical systems and guidance and navigation 
with the system nasa is phasing out controllers decipher 
multiple pages of data displayed on their computer screens all 
while monitoring dozens of blinking console lights each of which 
can signal two or more safe or unsafe conditions 
in the old system flight information is stored in two computers 
and displayed on every controllers console by comparison 
muratores system divides the data among individual consoles 
shaving precious seconds off the processing 
