<TEXT>
house banking committee members who want 
savings and loan owners to put up more of their own money when they 
make loans will be fighting to preserve a legislative victory when 
they resume work next week on president bushs bailout proposal 
after hours of debate the panel voted 3615 thursday to require 
sampl owners by january 1995 to risk 3 of tangible or real 
money capital for every 100 they lend 
treasury secretary nicholas f brady praised the action in a 
statement released after the vote even though the deadline is 3 
years later than the june 1991 date sought by the administration 
requiring sampls to put their own capital at risk ahead of the 
taxpayers money is the only way to prevent in the future the 
unsound business practices that contributed to the current 
crisis brady said 
bush is proposing to spend at least 157 billion over 10 years 
the bulk of it from taxpayers to close or merge failed sampls he 
also wants to restructure the regulatory system spend 50 million 
a year to investigate and prosecute fraud in sampls and boost capital 
requirements 
assistant treasury secretary david mullins said the panels 
adoption of a 3 percent layer of protection between sampl loans that 
could go sour and federal insurance funds was more important than 
the timetable for achieving it 
however consumer groups are worried about a subsequent 
amendment sponsored by rep bill mccollum rfla that would 
permit thrift institutions to continue to risk depositors funds in 
subsidiaries involved in highrisk investments such as junk bonds 
and commercial real estate 
its a pretty critical loophole said peggy miller a 
lobbyist for the consumer federation of america it erodes what 
was just passed 
the administration had proposed that institutions raise extra 
capital to back those subsidiaries and the committee chairman rep 
henry b gonzalez dtexas had attempted to compromise by giving 
institutions five years to come up with the money 
however the committee voted 2624 to adopt mccollums measure 
he argued that without it many institutions now operating safely 
and profitably with subsidiaries would not be able to raise the 
extra capital 
another amendment sponsored by rep barney frank dmass 
would permit federal regulators to count mortgage servicing 
contracts as capital such contracts which pay institutions to 
collect monthly payments from homeowners on behalf of investors who 
own the mortgages provide a steady source of income and can be 
sold if an institution is closed 
the overall capital measure has a series of interim targets 
beginning june 1 1990 when the tangible capital standard would 
become 15 percent it would move to 2 percent in january 1992 
225 percent in january 1993 and 2625 percent in january 1994 
before reaching the full 3 percent a year later 
the house committees standard is substantially stricter than 
the bill passed last week by the senate which would require 15 
percent tangible capital by june 1991 
current law provides for a 3 percent standard but contains many 
accounting loopholes that count intangible assets such as 
goodwill as capital 
at the end of last year more than a third of the solvent sampls 
60 billion in listed capital was composed of goodwill which 
represents the value an institutions customer loyalty and name 
recognition critics argue that goodwill evaporates when an 
institution fails and thus provides no protection to government 
deposit insurance funds 
according to the treasury department about twothirds of the 
nations 3000 sampls can meet the 3 percent tangible standard some 
of those that do not should be able to raise the money but about 
245 may have to seek merger partners it said 
institutions failing to meet the standard would be subject to 
growth restrictions and closer regulatory supervision 
rep floyd flake dny said he intends to offer an amendment 
monday that would provide more favorable treatment of goodwill he 
and others including the powerful chairman of the house rules 
committee rep claude pepper dfla argue that it is unfair to 
wipe out the goodwill because during the early 1980s regulators 
permitted the accounting break to otherwise healthy institutions in 
exchange for taking over ailing thrifts 
