<TEXT>
american women are more likely to need 
antipoverty assistance than men as they struggle to raise 
children on their own and cope with leaner times in old age a 
census bureau report shows 
more than one woman in five 205 percent received help from 
some major benefits program during a 32month study reported on by 
the bureau on thursday 
during the same period the public assistance programs aided 158 
percent of men in the nation somewhat less than one out of six 
john m mcneil of the bureaus housing and household economic 
statistics division said that the difference in need is largely the 
result of women raising children without a husband present and the 
preponderance of women in the older age groups 
when marriages break up women more often obtain custody of the 
children and those families more often lapse into poverty mcneil 
said in a telephone interview in addition a growing number of 
single women are raising families of their own he noted 
as of 1987 the bureau said 343 percent of families with a 
female householder fell below the poverty level by comparison 
125 percent of families with a male householder and no wife and 
only 60 percent of married couples fell below the poverty level 
the analysis showed that more than twothirds of people living 
in a femaleheaded household with no husband present throughout the 
study period received antipoverty benefits 671 percent 
the study found that 183 percent of all americans received 
benefits from at least one of six programs studied included were 
general assistance aid to families with dependent children 
supplemental security income medicaid federal food stamps and 
federal and state rent assistance 
benefits were more likely to go to minorities to the very young 
and to people who had not finished high school according to the 
report which covered the period from late 1983 to early 1986 
one of the more important findings was that the likelihood of 
receiving benefits was very closely tied to the number of months in 
which income fell below the poverty level mcneil said so in 
that sense the programs appear to be providing benefits to those 
who need them the most 
this was the first longterm look at recipients of benefits done 
by the bureau and thus no past rates were available for 
comparison mcneil said the study will be repeated in the future 
he said 
nearly half of black americans obtained help from one or more 
programs during the period at 485 percent the study said by 
comparison the rate was 342 percent for hispanics and 139 
percent for white americans 
blacks also were longerterm recipients of help averaging 112 
months of benefits during the study period hispanics averaged 74 
months of benefits while it was 26 months for white recipients 
overall women recipients averaged 44 months of benefits 
compared with 30 months for men 
by age people under age 18 were the leading group receiving 
benefits at 266 percent and the subgroup under age 6 managed a 
301 percent rate 
programs benefited 199 percent of people aged 18 to 24 while 
in the 25 to 44 group the rate was 147 percent for people aged 65 
and over the rate was 179 
benefits were most needed by innercity residents at 237 
percent the rate was 205 percent in rural areas and fell to only 
123 percent in the suburbs 
by region 207 percent of southerners received benefits 
followed by 180 percent in the west 168 percent in the northeast 
and 167 percent in the midwest 
the study was based on repeated interviews with 19900 
households across the country 
