<TEXT>
a new laser technique erases tattoos but spares 
the skin providing the first way to get rid of battleships 
hearts old lovers names or other such decorations without causing 
scars researchers say 
the treatment uses an intense beam of light called a ruby laser 
to blast away the colors beneath the skin 
i think this is the first truly nonscarring therapy for 
tattoos said dr r rox anderson of massachusetts general 
hospital 
dr charles taylor a member of andersons research team 
planned to present the results of the laser treatment today at a 
meeting of the society for investigative dermatology in washington 
doctors said the laser is almost painless too it produces a 
sensation something like a loosely snapped rubber band 
lasers are already widely used for removing tattoos but current 
models burn them off leaving permanent scars the new technique 
also produces high heat but its effects are much more selective 
it uses brief 100 millionwatt flashes of red light which is 
absorbed by the tattoo pigment the heat shatters the bits of 
pigment imbedded in the skin as well as the cells that hold them 
but it does not harm blood vessels or ordinary cells 
there is clearly a difference between this and other therapies 
that are used anderson said 
anderson said the procedure could become the standard treatment 
for removing tattoos after it is approved by the us food and drug 
administration perhaps within two years 
dr kenneth arndt of beth israel hospital in boston agreed 
when the ruby laser works well which looks to be a good deal 
of the time the skin remains normal he said thats 
extraordinary and its bringing fancy technology to the level 
where it can be useful for patient care 
anderson said that in testing so far on 13 people the laser 
completely erased about half of the tattoos and faded the rest 
however he said the initial study was intended to find the 
proper intensity of laser light and some patients received 
relatively low doses results may be better when higher levels are 
used routinely 
of 41 tatoos treated only one small patch of skin measuring 
less than a square inch became scarred 
the laser will not remove red pigment because it does not absorb 
the red light amateur tattoos come off more easily than 
professionally drawn tattoos which contain more color 
anderson said that after his team began experimenting with the 
ruby laser they discovered that a group of doctors in glasgow 
scotland had worked on the same approach and published preliminary 
results in a british journal 
unless burned or removed surgically tattoos are permanent the 
boston researchers said that most of the people they have treated 
so far got them while drunk 
one woman had her boyfriends initials tattooed when she was a 
teenager the next day she regretted it and always kept the 
tattoo covered with a bandage 
tattoos are drawn by puncturing the skin usually with needles 
and inserting pigment that remains after the wound heals over 
the variety of laser used in the new treatment was once widely 
tested for medical purposes but none of them seemed to work and it 
was abandoned the ruby laser is used largely for welding 
</TEXT>
