<TEXT>
in the year since the roof ripped off an aloha 
airlines jet and a flight attendant plunged to her death 
widespread changes have occurred in the industry that once believed 
a maintained aircraft could fly forever 
the boeing 737 involved had rolled off the assembly line in 1969 
and had 89000 cycles takeoffs and landings in a corrosive 
saltair environment 
the industry and the federal aviation administration had 
believed that metal fatigue in older airplanes especially cracking 
around rivets and corrosion could be discovered in regular visual 
inspections 
however in the aloha case investigators think dozens of minute 
cracks invisible to the human eye connected and allowed a piece 
of fuselage to blow out in an explosive decompression at 24000 
feet followed by a whole section of the plane 
