<TEXT>
a mistake by a csx corp dispatcher with 23 
years experience caused the april 6 derailment of amtraks silver 
star near emporia a federal investigator said 
gordon j inglis of the national transportation safety board 
said thursday that the dispatcher based at csxs new central 
dispatch center in jacksonville fla had radioed the engineer 
that the silver star would be switching tracks in emporia four 
miles beyond the point where the switch had been set emporia is 
about 50 miles south of richmond 
the engineer failed to slow for the switch because he didnt 
expect it so soon inglis said 
the train plowed into the switch at its normal cruising speed of 
59 mph instead of the recommended crossover speed of 15 mph 
both engines and the first eight cars of the 18car train jumped 
the track causing minor injuries to 34 of the trains 519 
passengers and 18 million in damage 
inglis said tests found no evidence of drug or alcohol use by 
anyone involved in the trains routing or operation 
he said the dispatcher had a perfect work record before the 
derailment the man is still at his post and likely will keep his 
job the investigator said 
the safety boards final report on the accident due in june 
probably will recommend changes in operating procedures at the 
dispatch center inglis said 
csx has about 19000 miles of track in 20 states plus 
washington dc and ontario canada 
