<TEXT>
a government report on friday suggested that 
financial arrangements between physicians and health care 
businesses to which they refer medicare patients may be helping to 
drive up costs in the federal health insurance program 
the report to congress by the department of health and human 
services inspector general found that one in seven medicare 
physicians has a financial interest in a health care business to 
which they refer their patients 
it also found that patients of these physicians receive far more 
laboratory and other services than patients of physicians who have 
no financial arrangements with health care businesses 
the report by inspector general richard kusserow stopped short 
of saying that financial arrangements between physicians and 
laboratories and other healthrelated businesses lead to 
unnecessary testing and higher medicare costs 
while we have demonstrated an association rather than a 
causality this finding is quite troubling the report said 
kusserow recommends that the health care financing 
administration the hhs agency that oversees medicare require 
healthcare providers billing the program to disclose the names of 
their physician owners and investors to the program he also 
recommends that all claims submitted for medicare payment contain 
the names of referring physicians 
hhs is developing regulations that would limit 
referringphysicians financial involvement in laboratories or 
clinics and a bill introduced in congress would generally prohibit 
physicians from referring medicare patients to health care 
businesses in which they hold a financial interest 
rep pete stark dcalif who introduced the legislation said 
friday in a statement that medicare patients and the taxpayer 
are paying tens of millons of dollars for needless tests caused by 
doctors referring patients to centers from which the doctor makes a 
profit because of the referral 
if we do not stop this practice and if it continues to 
spread the added cost to medicare and the american health care 
system will be billions of dollars per year stark said 
while many joint venture arrangements in the healthcare 
industry are legitimate kusserows office is distributing 12 
million copies of a fraud alert to the nations health care 
providers warning that certain arrangements violate the medicare 
and medicaid antikickback law 
the report found that about 15 percent of physicians who bill 
medicare have an ownership investment or compensation arrangement 
with health care businesses to which they refer patients 
it estimated that 12 percent of physicians who bill medicare 
have ownership or investment interests in health care businesses 
including testing laboratories to which they refer patients eight 
percent of medicare physicians have compensation arrangements with 
such businesses including space rental and consulting agreements 
and management services contracts discounting the overlap between 
the two groups about 15 percent have at least one or both types of 
financial interest 
also at least 25 percent of independent clinical laboratories 
and 27 percent of independent physiological laboratories are owned 
wholly or partly by referring physicians the report found 
in addition the report said that patients referred by 
physicians who own or invest in clinical laboratories received 45 
percent more clinical lab services than all medicare patients in 
general regardless of where they received the services this 
increased use of services cost the medicare program 28 million in 
1987 the report said 
certainly the utilization effect we have seen in the 
laboratory industries is cause for concern to the medicare 
program the report said 
the inspector generals office compiled its findings through 
surveys of about 3680 physicians and 1132 health care businesses 
as well as interviews with industry representatives and health care 
experts 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

