<TEXT>
the former administrator of a federal housing 
program faulted for mismanagement and favoritism defended his 
actions friday and said an agency investigative report was 
misleading 
thomas t demery former assistant secretary of the department 
of housing and urban development and former federal housing 
commissioner acknowledged documentation was lacking from the 
process that awarded hud contracts for rehabilitation of lowincome 
housing projects 
but demery said no favoritism was used to select winners and 
that he and thensecretary samuel r pierce jr instituted more 
formal and documented procedures for awarding contracts beginning 
this year shortly before both left the department 
hud secretary jack kemp meanwhile told a group of state 
legislators friday that the program was being abused by 
consultants and some folks who were making a phone call and getting 
a federal grant 
kemp shut down the program temporarily this week following 
release of an investigative report by the hud inspector general and 
blocked some 100 million in pending contracts subject to a new 
review of the program 
the report charged no criminal activity but the hud inspector 
general turned it over to the justice department for review 
the report described how former reagan administration figures 
including former top hud officials and other republicans collected 
big fees as consultants and in some cases became developers on 
projects to rehabilitate subsidized apartments for the poor 
kemp said the report showed the programs selections were 
based on the perception and reality of favoritism and abuse of 
nonpublic information 
