<TEXT>
a new federal regulation goes into effect 
saturday aimed at protecting consumers from used car sellers who 
change the odometer readings on cars 
the rule implementing the 1986 truth in mileage act requires 
that records be kept of automobile mileage and is intended to make 
it possible for a wouldbe buyer to trace the actual mileage of a 
vehicle 
although waivers have been given in several states that have 
said they need more time to change forms the law requires that 
motor vehicle titles issued after saturday must be printed so that 
counterfeiting and alterations can easily be detected 
it also requires that mileage readings be disclosed on the title 
whenever the car is sold if the title does not have a space for 
the odometer reading a separate disclosure statement is required 
used car dealers leasing companies and auto auctions must 
maintain records including the mileage of vehicles sold for at 
least five years 
federal laws prohibit tampering with odometers in 1987 the 
latest year for which the national highway traffic safety 
administration has a complete report 17 cases of largescale 
odometer fraud were sent to the justice department and five others 
to state enforcement agencies 
some of the cases led to civil action and eight federal grand 
jury indictments led to 14 criminal convictions said agency 
spokesman tim hurd 
</TEXT>
