<TEXT>
a ceasefire negotiated by the arab 
league was strained by repeated violations friday threatening a 
renewal of the shelling duels between lebanese christian and syrian 
troops that killed 273 people 
the truce that ended 52 days of bombardments also was 
jeopardized by differences of interpretation over who controls the 
ports the issue that started the fighting 
a police spokesman said syrians and their druse moslem allies 
fired sporadic salvos of rockets at the christian port of byblos 
from about 130 pm to nightfall but no casualties were reported 
the ceasefire went into effect at noon friday 
the spokesman said the christian gunners did not retaliate 
infractions are so far of a minor nature but they could 
collapse the ceasefire if they continue or intensify said the 
spokesman who was not identified in line with regulations 
he also said that at about 130 pm two howitzer shells fired 
from syriancontrolled mountains southeast of beirut hit the 
christian sector but caused no casualties 
on friday before the ceasefire began syrian troops and 
christian militiamen intermittently fired howitzer and mortar 
rounds across the green line that divides the capital into moslem 
west beirut and christian east beirut police reported they said 
there were no casualties 
during the 52 days of frequently heavy shelling at least 993 
people were wounded 
the truce was announced thursday at the end of an emergency 
meeting of arab foreign ministers in tunis tunisia 
the agreement provides for an unspecified number of arab 
observers to monitor the ceasefire thus loosening syrias grip as 
lebanons main powerbroker 
the ceasefire is the fourth attempt by the 22nation arab 
league to halt the fighting it was welcomed by the main parties to 
the conflict syria and lebanese christian army commander gen 
michel aoun 
aoun who had declared a war of liberation from syria 
called the truce the first step toward a broader panarab role in 
lebanon which would weaken syrias monopoly of the decisionmaking 
process in our country 
in damascus syria president hafez assads government said it 
is satisified with resolutions announced by the arab league 
syria initially sent its 40000 troops into lebanon in 1976 on a 
peacekeeping mandate from the league 
in washington state department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler 
said washington supported the decision to send in arab league 
observers she added that outside parties involved in lebanon must 
exercise utmost restraint under questioning ms tutwiler said 
that statement was a reference to syria 
a un spokesman in geneva said un secretarygeneral javier 
perez de cuellar would meet saturday with the chairman of the arab 
league committee that drafted the plan 
the meeting follows a statement by the un security council 
supporting the arab leagues peace efforts and urging that perez de 
cuellar make all possible efforts and contacts which could be 
deemed useful 
the league truce calls for lifting the air sea and land 
blockades imposed during the fighting 
an earlier statement from aouns cabinet welcomed lifting of 
blockades imposed on legal ports besieged by the syrian forces 
it said maritime agencies should instruct their ships to head 
to legal ports 
aoun appears to be maintaining a blockade of ports run by 
syrianbacked militias a step likely to jeopardize the truce 
moslem army brigade commanders said the ceasefire and the 
lifting of blockades were a whole package agreement 
the present confrontation broke out march 8 two days after aoun 
ordered a blockade of militiarun ports that deny the state 
treasury 100 million a year in customs dues 
druse warlord walid jumblatts militia retaliated by shelling 
the 310squaremile christian enclave syrian gunners joined 
the christian voice of lebanon radio the organ of the 
rightwing phalange party voiced concern the truce is mere 
security tranquilizers 
the syrianbacked moslem cabinet of acting premier salim hoss 
which competes with the aoun government in running lebanon pledged 
full cooperation in the truce 
it made no comment on aouns order friday that beirut 
international airport reopen the countrys only airport located 
on the edge of moslem west beirut closed march 12 after christian 
gunners targeted it a source close to hoss said the airport will 
stay closed until the moslem cabinet decides otherwise 
