<TEXT>
raul sendic founder of the extreme left tupamaros 
movement in uruguay died friday in paris where he was undergoing 
treatment for a neurological illness officials at the edouard rist 
clinic said he was 63 
sendic long suffered from neurological problems believed to be 
the result of torture in uruguayan prisons in the early 1970s he 
had lived in france for the past two years 
sendics tightly organized urban guerrilla cells were a model 
for central american argentine and chilean movements to follow 
the cells used cleancut youths from old families to infiltrate the 
government they sought to topple 
after 13 years in prison sendic was freed in 1985 along with 
many other political prisoners after the civilian government of 
president julio sanguinetti replaced uruguays military regime 
sendic organized strikes in the sugar cane fields and hunger 
marches in 196061 then changed to an urban guerrilla strategy 
with the founding in 1963 of the national liberation front 
the front is called the mln by its spanish initials but is 
better known as the tupamaros after tupac amaru an 18thcentury 
inca chief burned at the stake by the spaniards 
the tupamaros raided food warehouses redistributing their booty 
to the poor and later moved into kidnappings for ransom to raise 
money 
one such incident inspired the film state of siege by 
director costa gavras starring yves montand as the american 
advisor to the uruguayan police who was kidnapped and later killed 
the mlns first legal convention was held in december 1985 
where delegates voted to abandon armed struggle in favor of 
nonviolent political action with a marxist and nationalist 
program favoring labor and land reform 
sendic was wounded and captured by soldiers in september 1972 
he was held without trial for 12 years during which his family 
and human rights campaigners protested the conditions of his 
detention 
he was convicted and sentenced to 45 years in prison in 1984 
but released the following year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

