timber industry officials angrily accused 
environmentalists friday of using threats against the spotted owl 
as a propaganda hoax and promised to mount a national effort 
to preserve forest lands for logging 
the statements at a news conference appeared to dampen efforts 
by members of the northwests congressional delegation and 
environmentalists to negotiate a way to protect both logging jobs 
and the endangered owl 
prodded by environmentalists the federal fish and wildlife 
service this week recommended listing the northern spotted owl 
which inhabits forests from northern washington to northern 
california as a threatened species 
that would involve preserving a large number of acres of 
oldgrowth forest for the approximately 1500 breeding pairs of 
owls left each pair would require as much as 2200 acres under a 
draft forest service plan 
industry officials however contend that action could result in 
as many as 280000 job layoffs losses could reach 62 billion in 
payrolls 900 million in payments to local counties and 3 billion 
in timber receipts to the federal treasury said the national 
forest products association 
its warfare between the preservationists and the industry 
said bill pickell of the washington contract loggers association 
he accused enviros of using the spotted owl issue to bring 
logging in old growth forests to a halt 
by the time all these studies on owl populations are done 
five years from now i think well find that this is the biggest 
hoax thats ever been pulled on the american public he said 
but by that time if these timberland setasides are allowed 
to continue the devastation to the industry and the northwest 
economy will be equivalent to that hiroshima bomb 
gus kuehne director of the northwest independent forest 
manufacturers said the industry was forming a national group 
called the american forest resource alliance 
he said it would battle environmentalist efforts to make inroads 
against logging in all areas of the country and would back up 
industry efforts to seek federal legislation designating lands for 
logging 
kuehne said the industry would only sit down to the negotiating 
table over the spotted owl issue as part of national talks pitting 
environmental issues against timber issues 
the forest industry officials estimates of damage to the timber 
industry were disputed by jean durning of the wilderness societys 
office in seattle 
i am distressed with the exaggerated claims of job losses 
and money losses to the economy that the industry has been 
making she said 
