<TEXT>
the united states and kuwait agreed to 
remove the american flag from six kuwaitowned oil tankers that 
sailed under us protection during the iraqiran war in the 
persian gulf officials said friday 
the decision announced by the us maritime administration in 
washington ended two months of deadlock between us and kuwaiti 
officials over what had been assumed to be a routine matter when 
first announced last february 
according to official sources in the gulf and in washington the 
kuwaitis objected to a us legal provision stipulating that even 
after the vessels reverted to kuwaiti registry the united states 
would retain the right to requisition them for use in a national 
emergency 
the sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said kuwaiti 
officials rejected such a condition as infringing on kuwaiti 
sovereignty 
they said the two sides finally agreed that the tankers would be 
returned to kuwaits finance ministry rather than to the kuwait oil 
tanker co which actually operates them 
although the tanker company is wholly governmentowned the 
sources said us officials deemed the distinction sufficient for 
a waiver of kuwaits obligation to make the ships available to 
america 
walter oates a spokesman for the us maritime administration 
said he could not comment other than to say the agreement became 
effective as of thursday kuwaiti officials were not available to 
comment 
the six ships include two petrolem product tankers and four 
identical liquefied gas carriers they were among 11 kuwaitowned 
tankers reflagged by the united states in mid1987 entitling them 
to us naval escort 
iran at that time was attacking kuwaiti shipping because of 
kuwaits support for iraq in the war hostilities ended last aug 
20 with a unmediated ceasefire 
kuwait had set up a new company the chesapeake shipping co of 
dover del as ostensible us owners of the tankers chesapeake 
will sell the six ships back to kuwait in a transaction 
existing only on paper the sources said 
the other five tankers will continue to fly the stars and 
stripes at least until next february on condition that 
allamerican crews replace the regular crews during that period 
at the time of the reflagging in 1987 the reagan administration 
waived a us law requiring usflagged ships to have allamerican 
crews 
