<TEXT>
spring has kissed central alabama and 
lc crosby once again is busy planting corn peas butter beans 
and okra hes also hoping for a bumper watermelon crop this summer 
ive got a plan he says as he leans against his old ford 
tractor if it works out im going to get my watermelons on the 
market two or three weeks earlier than anybody else and ill clean 
up 
crosby a friendly man with a wiry build becomes excited as he 
talks about his crops and the 43acre dream farm where he and 
his family once worked as field hands however this could be the 
last spring for his dream and for a lot of other dreams like his 
at 33 lc crosby is a young black farmer and as such hes 
twice as likely to lose his land as his white counterpart 
in 1910 the nations 950000 black farmers comprised 14 percent 
of all farmers in this country now the remaining 35000 make up 
just 16 percent of the 23 million farmers in the united states 
according to the us census bureau the number of black farms 
declined by 42 percent between 1978 and 1982 white farms fell by 
only 24 percent during the same period 
unless this trend is reversed there will be no more black 
farmers in america by the year 2000 this dire prediction is 
contained in the us civil rights commissions 1982 report on the 
decline of black farmers in america 
yet while theres just a relative handful of young black 
farmers still operating the current median age for us black 
farmers is 60 the federal government is trying to force lc 
crosby off his land 
the fha farmers home administration has given him notice to 
vacate the premises because hes behind on his loan but were 
telling him to stay put and fight says george paris jr a 
field coordinator for the private nonprofit federation of 
southern cooperatives 
crosby bought his farm which includes a large pond and 
fiveacre pecan orchard at an fha auction in 1985 he bid 36500 
borrowing 31000 from the government 
my annual payment is 3800 he said i fell behind the 
second year now ive got the money to make the payment but the 
fha wants the whole 30000 
paris said hes heard that a wealthy white landowner whose bid 
was 10000 lower than crosbys covets the property 
its the same old story he said the fha is slowly 
changing but basically at the local level quite often its still a 
bunch of good ol white boys who look after each other 
paris father who worked for the fha for nearly 30 years and 
was one of the first black men ever to serve as an assistant county 
supervisor agrees with this assessment 
it was tragic blacks always got the last and the least 
said the elder paris adding that he saw hundreds of black 
alabamians lose their farms during the 30 years he workd for the 
fha 
i remember one time back in the 60s i was told outright 
by a white fha committee member in bullock county ala that a 
black farmer had been denied a loan because he was shooting off 
his mouth about civil rights 
under the fhas loan procedure a county supervisor makes a 
recommendation to a threemember county loan committee which then 
either approves or denies the loan fred bennett a 73yearold 
farmer in the mt zion community near greenville was the first 
black ever to serve on an fha county committee 
in this country the average blackowned farm contains fewer 
than 100 acres compared with an average of 440 acres for all us 
farms bennett and his wife lena own 500 acres which they slowly 
acquired over the past 40 years parcel by parcel 
my grandfather came to this area at age 12 shortly after he 
was freed from slavery bennett said he never owned land 
being a cash renter but ive found that for a black man in this 
country there is no greater security nor better avenue to 
independence than farming 
bennett who said he and his four brothers pooled their 
resources and pulled together toward a common objective 
acknowledged he is worried and saddened that this generation of 
young blacks isnt going into agriculture 
after the civil war the federal government promised the freed 
blacks 40 acres and a mule but hardly any of them got it he 
said our people should realize by now that theyve got to help 
themselves nobodys going to do it for them 
im very concerned that young blacks are turning their backs 
on farming at a time when life in the cities is getting worse 
every day 
the united farmers organization a nonprofit advocacy group 
based in charlotte nc estimates there now are fewer than 200 
fulltime black farmers aged 25 or under in the entire country 
officials at north carolina aampt state university who say they 
are getting 25 percent fewer agriculture students than they did 20 
years ago blame farmings poor image and the enormous difficulty 
young blacks face in amassing capital 
the continuing phenomenon of black land loss was the topic at a 
recent meeting sponsored by the university and the united church of 
christ 
greed and institutional racism are the major reasons blacks 
have been forced out of farming said the rev charles shelby rooks 
director of the churchs board of homeland ministries in his 
keynote address at the conference in greensboro nc 
in its report the us civil rights commission found that 
blacks were being illserved by the fha the us department of 
agricultures agency designed specifically to help poor farmers 
the commission noting that black farmers 90 percent of whom 
are in the south often are unable to deal with the ever more 
complex federal loan programs the commission called for serious 
government intervention 
last july as part of an omnibus farm bill passed by congress in 
1987 the fha launched its socially disadvantaged outreach farm 
ownership program 
so far said fha spokesman nolan kegley we have made 58 
loans to minority farmers under the program he said the loans 
totalling 46 million are to finance farm purchases for poor 
blacks and other minorities 
we recognize the problems of the past and were working on 
them at all levels kegley said since 1984 the percentage of 
fha loans to blacks has been steadily increasing 
he acknowledged when asked however that only 91 of the fhas 
1849 county supervisors are black in mississippi the state with 
the most black farmers eight of the 82 county supervisors are 
black in north carolina its only three of 79 
fha officials in those states say they have had little luck 
recruiting qualified blacks because the goverment pay scale isnt 
competitive 
