<DOCNO> AP890428-0214 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
south korea and taiwan need to do more to 
allow their currencies to rise in relation to the us dollar as a 
way of lowering huge trade surpluses the two nations are running 
with the united states according to a government report 
the report the treasury department sent to congress on thursday 
followed six months of negotiations the united states has held with 
both countries 
the united states has been pressuring the nations to allow their 
currencies to rise in value in relation to the dollar as a way of 
making their products more expensive on american markets and making 
us goods cheaper in their markets 
while saying that both nations have made some progress in 
boosting the value of their currencies the report contended that 
much more needs to be done 
the department said it would press forward with the negotiations 
in the hope of achieving further progress the negative findings 
were likely to increase pressure on the two governments in 
congress where lawmakers have long been unhappy with the trade 
practices of the two nations 
last october an initial treasury report had singled out taiwan 
and south korea for manipulating their currencies to gain an 
unfair competitive advantage in world markets 
taiwan and south korea have for many years used part of the 
money earned through their trade surpluses to buy and sell 
currencies on the open market to have an impact on the price of 
their own currencies in relation to the dollar 
by keeping their currencies from rising as much against the 
dollar as other currencies have they have been able to keep the 
prices of their exports to the united states from rising the 
practice has also made it harder for american industry to take 
advantage of a cheaper dollar in selling goods to taiwan and korea 
in 1988 the united states had a merchandise trade deficit of 
95 billion with south korea and 13 billion with taiwan meaning 
that the two countries accounted for 18 percent of americas total 
trade deficit last year 
the treasurys report to the congress on international 
economic and exchange rate policy said that the assessment six 
months ago that the us trade deficit would continue to improve 
this year had been clouded by recent developments such as rising 
oil prices 
the treasury did not forecast a new trade figure however many 
private analysts fear that the trade deficit which dropped 
dramatically in 1988 because of the decline of the value of the 
dollar against many major currencies could even begin rising again 
unless the dollar fell further 
the report was prepared under a provision of the trade act of 
1988 which requires the administration to look for cases of 
currency manipulation by american competitors in world trade and to 
embark on bilateral negotiations to halt such practices 
</TEXT>
