japans current account surplus shrank 89 percent 
in 1988 the second straight year in which the surplus in the broad 
trade measure has contracted the finance ministry said friday 
analysts said the decline to 7697 billion in fiscal 1988 from 
1987s 8447 billion was an encouraging sign for japan which is 
trying to reduce its trade imbalance to ease tensions with its 
trading partners 
the current account is a comprehensive measurement of a nations 
international trade flows and includes imports and exports of goods 
and services earnings and expenditures on tourism financial 
investments and other transactions 
the ministry said import growth outpaced export growth in the 
fiscal year which ended march 31 imports grew 233 percent to 
17183 billion from 13940 billion the previous year while 
exports rose 144 percent to 26710 billion from 23344 billion 
strong domestic demand for manufactured goods helped boost 
imports ministry officials said 
japans current account surplus for march announced at the same 
time shrank to 632 billion from 833 billion a year earlier 
the ministry said the surplus was also smaller than februarys 
771 billion 
both exports and imports in the current account balance are 
measured when contracts are settled and are different from the 
customsclearance trade statistics that the ministry announces 
separately each month 
the ministry announcement did not include breakdowns of trade 
figures by country or region 
