<TEXT>
did the great bull market on wall street 
secretly survive the crash of 1987 
has it now as in some sciencefiction movie sequel crawled out 
of the disasters rubble and begun to prowl the canyons of wall 
street once more 
those questions are being raised in many investors minds as the 
rally in stock prices that began in the waning weeks of 1987 
carries to new high after new high 
as of late last week the dow jones industrial average stood 
nearly 700 points or 40 percent above its low on black monday oct 
19 1987 
a 40 percent rise in 18 months compares pretty favorably with 
many a past rally that earned the bull market stamp as if to 
confirm its status the economy has kept growing at a robust rate 
showing scarcely any effects from a very scary financial event 
but one prominent money manager contends that people who think 
this way might be falling into a dangerous trap 
if you judge the stock market by price alone the bull appears 
to have revived concedes henry gailliot senior vice president at 
pittsburghbased federated research corp which manages assets 
totaling 37 billion 
when you apply other traditional criteria however it doesnt 
look at all like a bull market gailliot said in an interview 
in a bull market he says a broad array of stocks should be 
rising to keep pace with the narrow sample represented by the dow 
jones industrials but that hasnt been happening 
while the averages have hit new postcrash highs the number of 
individual stocks at new 52week peaks has been unimpressive he 
adds 
volume is not rising with price he also observes the 
rally to date continues to have the characteristics of a bear 
market rally we expect a new low below djia 1740 in price before 
this bear market is over 
for some time now gailliot like many other economists has been 
predicting a recession that has yet to give any sign of showing up 
what has confounded the forecasters he says has been 
persistent strength in spending by consumers long since 
overextended by the usual yardsticks 
since consumer spending accounts for twothirds of economic 
activity the consumer is the gorilla of our economy he 
observes 
if you dont get the consumer right you dont get the 
business cycle right 
consumers ability to keep spending has been stretched in the 
1980s gailliot says by devices such as low or no rate auto 
financing and home equity lines of credit these are marvelous 
innovations that do nothing but let the consumer go farther out on 
the limb 
at some point he says consumers will reach the stage where 
they want or are forced to retrench 
when the gorilla decides how much is enough he says then 
you get a recession 
</TEXT>
