<TEXT>
former teamsters president roy lee williams 
died today at his farm home after a lengthy bout with emphysema and 
heart problems 
williams 73 was released from federal prison in september 
after serving three years of a 10year sentence for attempting to 
bribe a senator over trucking legislation 
williams served as international president of the teamsters 
union from 198183 
he was forced to resign as teamsters chief after he and four 
codefendants were convicted in december 1982 for trying to bribe 
former us sen howard cannon of nevada to influence trucking 
deregulation cannon was not charged in the case 
though he maintained his innocence during the 1982 trial 
williams acknowledged his role in the conspiracy case during 
testimony in 1985 in a kansas city trial he was cooperating with 
federal authorities investigating the mob in an attempt to have his 
own sentence reduced 
williams testified that while he was a kansas city labor leader 
before his elevation to the teamsters presidency he had been under 
the control of nick civella the reputed crime boss in kansas city 
at the time 
he said he received payoffs of 1500 a month from civella for 
seven years until he became teamsters president he said civella 
who has since died played a key role in his election to the union 
presidency 
williams also testified by videotape in a federal court trial in 
new york against mob fitures accused of fixing his election as 
teamsters president and that of his successor jackie presser who 
died last july three codefendants were acquitted of that charge 
in may 1988 but convicted of unrelated charges 
