<TEXT>
the midwest stock exchange in an attempt to 
capture a share of the afterhours trading of us stocks is 
proposing a second computerized trading session officials said 
thursday 
the new trading session from 330 pm to 5 pm cdt would be 
for the trading of portfolios and not for individual customers 
said vice president roger hendrick 
the midwest exchange is currently open from 830 am to 3 pm 
cdt most of the stocks traded on the exchange are also traded on 
the new york stock exchange 
the exchange applied wednesday to the securities and exchange 
commission for approval 
hendrick estimated that stock portfolios traded after hours 
equal 10 million to 20 million shares daily but the activity is 
not reflected in reported trading volume and the volume is 
difficult to accurately measure 
hendrick said the portfolios traded in the late afternoon will 
be required to consist of at least 20 stocks none of which may be 
greater than 10 percent of the value of the portfolio 
brokerage firms trading portfolios will send their transactions 
electronically into a computer at the midwest exchange which will 
record the trade 
currently such trades are registered on the london stock 
exchange to comply with new york stock exchange rules that member 
brokerages trade on recognized exchanges when it is closed 
hendrick said the midwest exchange will charge a fee to record 
the portfolio trades which are recorded free of charge in london 
</TEXT>
